This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) which are widely used in computer vision tasks. Additionally, the paper discusses the functionality and redundancy of convolutional filters, which are specific to CNNs. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques, which makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Neural Networks (cs.NE) is another likely sub-category as the paper deals with pruning convolutional filters in a neural network. 

Finally, the paper discusses the interpretation of filter functionality, which involves natural language processing techniques. Therefore, it could also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
